    <Content>
        <Paragraph><Bold>Marriages between angels and women is just an absurd, ridiculous, heretical, and blasphemous
            teaching</Bold></Paragraph>
        <Paragraph><Bold>Russellists have fabricated the blasphemous teaching that once there was a time in which many angels
            married
            women</Bold>. This is totally false. Angels have neither power nor wisdom to create a human body; nor
            would God
            cooperate with them by creating a body with the sole purpose to commit such a horrid sin. In the
            "Watchtower", a
            magazine of the Russellists, they often present this teaching.</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph> In order to support their error they present Gn 1-4, from which they have far fetched their fabrication.
            Sadly, they
            have "infected" true Christians, who are now believing the filthy idea. According to the "Governing Body" of
            the
            Russellists, a great number of angels, some how, incarnated themselves, and had "sons" with regular women.
            <Bold>Not
                true</Bold>.</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph> To prop their teaching, Russellists allege that in Job 1: 6 the angels are called "sons of God", therefore,
            <Bold>necessarily</Bold>,
            those who were called "sons of God" in Genesis, have to also be angels. Let's first demonstrate biblically,
            and
            later using common sense, that this is another lie.</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph> "<i>1 And it came to pass, when men began to multiply on the face of the earth, and daughters were born unto
            them, 2
            <Bold>that the sons of God saw</Bold> the daughters of men that they were fair; and they took them wives
            of all
            which they chose. 3 <Bold>And the LORD said, My spirit shall not always strive with man</Bold>, for that
            he also
            is flesh; yet his days shall be an hundred and twenty years. 4 <Bold>There were giants in the earth in
                those days;
                and also after that, when the sons of God came in unto the daughters of men</Bold>, and they bare
            children to
            them, the same became mighty men which were of old, men of renown. 5 And GOD saw that the wickedness of man
            was
            great in the earth, and that every imagination of the thoughts of his heart was only evil continually. 6 And
            it
            repented the LORD that he had made man on the earth, and it grieved him at his heart</i>." ( Gn 6: 1-4 )</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph></Paragraph>
        <Paragraph> "<i>Now there was a day when the sons of God came to present themselves before the LORD, <Bold>and Satan
            came also
            among them</Bold></i>." ( Job 1: 6 )</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph><Bold>In the Bible, human beings have been called "sons of God" many times more than the angels</Bold>.
            Why then
            do the Russellists make believe that in Gn 6: 1-4 the phrase "sons of God" refers to angels and not men?</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph><Bold>Most probably, these men were called "sons of God", and these women were called "daughters of men",
            meaning
            that</Bold> men who were believers and pious, married women who were unbelievers, carnal, sensual, and
            given to
            the flesh. Men did so because these women were gorgeous, beautiful, and paid no attention to their faith,
            and
            subsequently their soul. This interpretation of Gn 6: 1-2 agrees with the complaint God expresses in verse
            3.
            Certainly so, after saying in verse 2 the wrongs of the so called "sons of God", God said: "<i>My spirit
                shall not
                always strive <Bold>with man</Bold></i>…". <Bold>We see that God did not mention angels</Bold>,
            who, in
            this case, would be the main subjects of the problem, ( if truly this teaching was right.)</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph> "… <Bold>the sons of God saw</Bold> <i>the daughters of men that they were fair; and they took them
            wives of all
            which they chose. <Bold>And the LORD said, My spirit shall not always strive with man</Bold>, for that
            he also
            is flesh; yet his days shall be an hundred and twenty years</i>." ( Gn 6: 2-3 )</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph><Bold>Something else to consider, is that verse 2 does not say that "the sons of God" took a body of flesh
            and
            bones</Bold>, as to be able to have sexual relations with women. It comes with the territory that if the
            phrase
            "sons of God" would refer to angels, the writer would explain that they took a body, because he had to know
            that no
            one would otherwise understand how an angel could have sex with a woman.</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph><Bold>It is far more logical to admit that the problem was caused by the believer's blinded lechery,
            leading them
            to marry without any regard for their religion</Bold>. Because of the fact that every believer had taken
            this
            wrong path, we see that God considered it better to destroy that society, and start another with Noah, who
            was a man
            of great qualities.</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph><Bold>Now, to understand what I am about to say, it is necessary to realize that the 5th chapter of Genesis
            is a
            list of genealogies, inserted between Gn 4: 26 and 6: 1</Bold>. If you jump from verse 4: 26 to 6: 1 you
            will not
            notice an interruption, but on the contrary, reading becomes more sequential and fluent. You will even see
            that
            chapter 5 begin by stating: "This is the book of the generations of Adam". This was probably a parchment
            inserted
            between Gn 4: 26 and 6: 1.</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph> After understanding this previous explanation we realize that subsequent to saying in verse 4: 26 "<Bold>And
            to
            Seth, to him also there was born a son; and he called his name Enos. Then men began to call upon the name of
            the
            LORD"</Bold>, right afterwards in 6: 1-2 we see the complaint that "the sons of God" (descendants of
            faithful
            Enos, those who called themselves by the name of the Lord ), married the daughters of men, ( those who did
            not call
            themselves by the name of the Lord, maybe because they were descendants of Cain ). The importance of the
            problem is
            that by marrying believers to non believers, the society was going to corrupt entirely. All this proves that
            the
            phrase "sons of God" referred to men who were believers, and the phrase "daughters of men" referred to women
            who
            were unbelievers.</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph><Bold>It will become evident that human-beings are called "sons of God" over and over again, just by
            reading</Bold> Psalm 82: 6; Hosea 1: 10; Ro 8: 14, 16, 19 &amp; 21; 9: 26; Gal 3: 26; 4: 6; Philippians 2:
            15 and
            many
            others.</Paragraph>
        <Paragraph> "<i>I have said, Ye are gods; and all of <Bold>you are children of the most
            High</Bold></i><Bold>.</Bold>" (
            Psalm 82: 6 )</Paragraph>
